# Testing

## Tooling
- JUnit 5, AssertJ, Mockito (all from `spring-boot-starter-test`).
- H2 (in-memory) for `@DataJpaTest` and `@SpringBootTest` slices when speed matters.
- Testcontainers Postgres only if a slice cannot run on H2 (e.g. uses Postgres-specific JSONB or `@SQLRestriction` SQL that differs). Document the choice in the test class JavaDoc.

## Where tests live
- `src/test/java/com/att/tdp/issueflow/<feature>/<ClassUnderTest>Test.java` — unit tests with Mockito.
- `src/test/java/com/att/tdp/issueflow/<feature>/<Controller>WebMvcTest.java` — `@WebMvcTest` slice tests, mocking the service.
- `src/test/java/com/att/tdp/issueflow/<feature>/<Repository>JpaTest.java` — `@DataJpaTest`.
- `src/test/java/com/att/tdp/issueflow/IssueFlowApplicationTests.java` — boot smoke test (already exists).
- `src/test/resources/application.yaml` — H2 datasource for tests.

## Naming
- `@DisplayName` per method describing the behavior, not the method name.
- Method pattern: `should<Behavior>_when<Condition>()`.
- Example: `should_return409_whenStatusTransitionIsBackward()`.

## What to cover (per slice — non-negotiable)
- Every service method with branching logic: one test per branch (happy path, each error path, each FSM transition).
- Every controller: at least one happy-path `@WebMvcTest` and one error-path test per endpoint.
- Cross-cutting concerns (locking, FSM, soft delete, RBAC) get dedicated tests, not just incidental coverage.

## Don't
- Don't test framework code (Spring MVC routing, JPA mechanics).
- Don't write tests that only assert mocks were called — assert observable behavior (returned value, persisted state, audit row written).
- Don't share mutable state across tests. Reset via `@BeforeEach` or use `@Transactional` rollback on integration tests.
- Don't load the full `@SpringBootTest` unless the slice tests are insufficient.

## Gotchas (learned the hard way)
- **`@WebMvcTest(controllers = X.class)` only *filters* which controllers to load from the main-app component scan — it does NOT register a controller class declared *inside the test file*.** If you write a dummy controller as an inner class for testing (e.g. to exercise `GlobalExceptionHandler` arms), you MUST also list it in `@Import(...)`, alongside any `@RestControllerAdvice` you want active. Symptom when missed: every request returns 500 because Spring routes to `ResourceHttpRequestHandler` and the catch-all maps `NoResourceFoundException` → 500. Always sanity-check with `andDo(print())` (look at `Handler` and `Resolved Exception`) when a `@WebMvcTest` returns an unexpected status.
- When asserting status codes in handler tests, **always pair the status assertion with a `$.code` assertion** so a coincidental 500 from a different code path doesn't accidentally satisfy a 500-expected test.
- **Once `spring-boot-starter-security` is on the classpath, every `@WebMvcTest` gets Spring Security's default filter chain (every endpoint → 401).** For tests that are exercising controller / handler logic (not authn/authz), add `@AutoConfigureMockMvc(addFilters = false)` to skip filters. Cover real authn/authz behavior in a dedicated `SecurityIntegrationTest` (`@SpringBootTest` slice). Symptom when missed: every existing `@WebMvcTest` suddenly returns 401 and your status assertions fail with `expected:<200> but was:<401>`.
- **Custom `OncePerRequestFilter` subclasses should be registered as explicit `@Bean`s, not `@Component`s.** `@WebMvcTest` includes `Filter` types in its web slice, so a `@Component`-annotated custom filter gets auto-discovered even in unrelated controller tests. If that filter's dependencies (e.g. a `@Service`-annotated `JwtService`) are not in the web slice, the context fails to load with `UnsatisfiedDependencyException`. Register the filter via `@Bean` in `SecurityConfig` instead. Combined with `addFilters = false`, slice tests then ignore the filter entirely.
- **`@DataJpaTest` runs in a single transaction → JPA's first-level cache returns the SAME managed reference for repeated `findById()` calls on the same row.** Trying to simulate two concurrent clients via two `findById` calls inside one test method DOES NOT WORK — both handles point to the same in-memory object, so a `saveAndFlush` on one mutates the other and the supposed "stale" handle is no longer stale by the time you try to write it. Symptom: optimistic-locking tests pass without ever exercising the conflict path. **Fix:** hand-build a detached entity with an explicitly stale `@Version` field (set the id + version + mutated fields directly on a fresh POJO), then `saveAndFlush(stale)` — merge will detect the version mismatch and throw `ObjectOptimisticLockingFailureException`.
- **H2 with `DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1` persists rows across test CLASSES in the same JVM, NOT just methods.** `@DataJpaTest` rolls back the *current* test's transaction but cannot reach rows committed earlier by a non-`@Transactional` `@SpringBootTest` (e.g. our `AuditIntegrationTest`). Symptom: `@DataJpaTest` count assertions are off by N depending on which other test classes Surefire ran first. **Fix in `@DataJpaTest`:** call `repo.deleteAll(); em.flush()` at the top of `@BeforeEach` to defensively wipe any leakage from another class. **Fix in the polluter:** make it `@Transactional` if you can, or explicitly clean up in `@AfterEach`/`@AfterAll`. Note: `@Transactional` on the polluter breaks cross-cutting tests where the audited writes themselves need to be visible post-call (because audit rows are written inside the same txn that gets rolled back); in that case the defensive wipe in `@DataJpaTest` is the more robust fix.
- **`@WebMvcTest` + `@PreAuthorize` requires `@EnableMethodSecurity` in scope, BUT importing it via a nested `@Configuration` test class breaks controller registration** (the AOP proxy interferes with `RequestMappingHandlerMapping` scanning and every URL returns 404). When the controller has `@PreAuthorize` and you need to test the 403 branch: cover it in a `@SpringBootTest` integration test with a real login, not in `@WebMvcTest`. The `@WebMvcTest` (with `addFilters=false`) silently ignores `@PreAuthorize`, which is *fine* for testing happy-path controller logic — just don't try to verify 403 there.
- **`@RestController` + `@PreAuthorize` at the class level + non-RESTful endpoints (e.g. `POST /users/update/{id}`) are easy to mistype in integration tests.** When writing an integration test that posts to a non-RESTful endpoint, verify the verb by grepping the controller's `@PostMapping`/`@PatchMapping`/etc., not by assuming `PATCH /{resource}/{id}`. Slice 7's first AuditIntegrationTest run was a 500 because the test used `PATCH /users/{id}` but the actual mapping is `POST /users/update/{id}`.
- **With `GenerationType.IDENTITY` (our `BaseEntity` default), `em.persist()` issues the INSERT synchronously — NOT at the next `em.flush()`.** Hibernate needs the auto-generated id back before persist returns, so the SQL fires inside `persist`. Tests asserting unique-constraint violations on direct `EntityManager` calls should write `assertThatThrownBy(() -> em.persist(dup))`, not `() -> em.flush()`. (Sequence-based id generators DO defer to flush — this is IDENTITY-specific.) Symptom when missed: the test method returns successfully and the constraint violation manifests as a test-runner ERROR (not FAILURE) because the exception fires from the surrounding test infrastructure's rollback, not from any assertion. Slice 8 caught this on `TicketDependencyRepositoryJpaTest.should_rejectDuplicatePair_atDbLevel`.
- **Test classes in a sub-package (e.g. `dependencies/`) cannot read package-private constants from the production class (`dependencies/service/`).** Either bump the constant to `public` OR inline the literal in the test with a comment pinning it to the spec. We prefer the inline literal — it makes the test a contract guard ("anyone bumping the cap will trip this test AND should update prompts.md"), instead of being silently kept in sync.
- **Hibernate `@SQLDelete` on a `@Version`-bearing entity requires a TWO-placeholder SQL.** Hibernate's parameter binding always passes `(id, version)` for any DELETE on a versioned entity, regardless of what your custom SQL looks like. A single-`?` SQL like `UPDATE tickets SET deleted_at = NOW() WHERE id = ?` fires at test time with H2 error 90008 "Invalid value 2 for parameter parameterIndex". Correct shape: `UPDATE tickets SET deleted_at = NOW() WHERE id = ? AND version = ?`. (Entities without `@Version` are fine with one placeholder — Project in slice 9 demonstrates this.) **Symptom that confused us in slice 9:** `@DataJpaTest` repository tests passed (they roll back the txn before commit-time SQL fires); ALL `@SpringBootTest` classes failed on `@BeforeEach`'s `deleteAll()`.
- **`Spring PageImpl(content, pageable, total)` SILENTLY "corrects" the total when `pageable.offset + pageable.pageSize > total` AND content is non-empty.** It sets total to `offset + content.size()`. This is a "last-page consistency fix" — reasonable in prod where pageSize is small relative to total, but breaks Mockito tests that fixture a stubbed `PageImpl<>(List.of(2-items), PageRequest.of(0, 10), 2L)` and expect `getTotalElements()` to be 2 — it gets corrected to whatever-the-mapping-step-produces. **Fix:** in test fixtures, set `pageSize` equal to the content size when total is small (`PageRequest.of(0, 2)` for content of 2). Slice 10's race-window test caught this — initial pageSize=10/total=2 → reported total=1 (off by one). Don't fight the constructor; size the fixture appropriately.
- **Username regex `[A-Za-z0-9_]{3,32}` (spec 01) does NOT accept hyphens.** Integration-test fixtures with hyphenated usernames (e.g. `mt-author`) will silently FAIL the mention extractor's lookup, because the regex stops at the first invalid character (`@mt-author` extracts `mt` — 2 chars, below min). Symptom: integration tests that depend on the user's own username resolving (self-mention, fixture round-trip) fail with empty mentions. Use underscores: `mt_author`. Same risk applies anywhere a username has to round-trip through a parser (spec 01's allowlist character class).
- **Cross-class H2 contamination — unique-constraint collisions on common usernames.** `@SpringBootTest` classes (which COMMIT rows) leave seed users like `alice`, `bob` in the in-mem DB across test classes within one Surefire run. A `@DataJpaTest` running later that tries to seed its own `alice` hits `UK_USERS_USERNAME`. **Fix in the `@DataJpaTest`:** namespace your fixture usernames with a class/test-scoped prefix (e.g. `mrjt-1-alice`) so the seeded rows are guaranteed unique regardless of who ran before. This is a sibling of the slice-7 wipe-with-deleteAll Gotcha but applies to unique constraints we'd violate even if we DID wipe (because the `@DataJpaTest` rollback doesn't actually delete-then-flush; it just rolls back at the end). Slice 10 caught this on `MentionRepositoryJpaTest` after `MentionsIntegrationTest` populated `alice`/`bob`.
- **`OncePerRequestFilter.shouldNotFilterAsyncDispatch()` defaults to `true`** — meaning the filter is SKIPPED on async re-dispatches (Servlet 3+ async like `Callable`, `DeferredResult`, `StreamingResponseBody`, SSE). Combined with a `STATELESS` Spring Security config + a JWT-style filter that does `try/finally { SecurityContextHolder.clearContext(); }`, the async re-dispatch arrives with an empty `SecurityContext` and `AuthorizationFilter` denies the request. Symptom: every existing test passes; the FIRST async-returning controller you ship hits 500 "response already committed" wrapping `AuthorizationDeniedException: Access Denied` for any authenticated endpoint. **Fix:** override `shouldNotFilterAsyncDispatch()` to return `false` in the JWT filter — re-extract the bearer header on async dispatch and re-populate the context (the existing `try/finally` clear is idempotent and harmless on repeated invocations). Slice 11 caught this on `CsvIntegrationTest` — `StreamingResponseBody` from `GET /tickets/export` was the codebase's first async controller. The bug had lived in `JwtAuthenticationFilter` since slice 3 but had never been exercised.
- **H2 in `MODE=PostgreSQL` rejects the `BLOB` type that Hibernate's `H2Dialect` emits for `@Lob byte[]`.** Symptom on the first `@Lob` entity you add: schema generation fails at startup with `Unknown data type: "BLOB"; SQL statement: create table X (... data blob not null ...)` and every test referencing the table errors with `Table "X" not found`. The mismatch: `org.hibernate.dialect.H2Dialect` produces vanilla H2 DDL (which uses `BLOB`), but the connection URL's `MODE=PostgreSQL` flag turns off H2's native BLOB type in favour of PostgreSQL's `BYTEA`. **Fix:** annotate the field with `@Column(columnDefinition = "BYTEA")` — `BYTEA` is the canonical PostgreSQL type (so production PostgreSQL is happy) AND H2-in-PG-mode accepts it as an alias (so the test JVM is happy). No test-only conditional, no two datasource configs, one annotation. Slice 12 caught this on `AttachmentRepositoryJpaTest` (the codebase's first `@Lob` field).
- **`MissingServletRequestPartException` is NOT covered by Spring Boot's default web error handlers when a `@RestControllerAdvice` catches `Exception.class`.** A `@RequestParam("file") MultipartFile` declared in a controller method, with the request omitting that part, throws `MissingServletRequestPartException` which falls through to the catch-all `Exception` arm and returns 500 `INTERNAL_ERROR` — definitely not what a client missing a required form field deserves (the expected mapping is 400 `MISSING_PARAMETER`, mirroring the existing handler for `MissingServletRequestParameterException`). **Fix:** add an explicit `@ExceptionHandler(MissingServletRequestPartException.class)` to `GlobalExceptionHandler` that returns 400 `MISSING_PARAMETER` with the part name in the message. Slice 12's `AttachmentControllerWebMvcTest.upload_missingFilePart_returns400` caught this; the same gap existed in slice 11's CSV controller but was not exercised by the slice-11 tests (which always sent the part).
- **Integration tests that assert audit-log row counts MUST clear `auditLogs.deleteAll()` AFTER calling `/auth/login`** — the login flow itself writes a `LOGIN/USER` audit row (slice 3 wiring + slice 7's `AuditLogService.logAs` overload). Without the wipe, every subsequent count assertion is off by N=number-of-login-calls. The polluting row even survives manual `wipe` in `@BeforeEach` if the login happens AFTER the wipe (i.e. inside the test method, as is typical because login needs the seeded user to already exist). Pattern: `wipe → seed users/projects → login → auditLogs.deleteAll() → exercise the code under test → count rows`. Slice 13's `AutoAssignIntegrationTest` caught this on first run: two tests expected 2 rows but got 3 (LOGIN + CREATE + AUTO_ASSIGN), and one expected 0 but got 1 (just LOGIN). The CSV integration test had the right pattern from slice 11 (clears after login), which is why it didn't trip on the same boundary.
